# Roguebusters Architecture

This is a Rust roguelike using **bracket-lib** (rendering/input) and **specs** (ECS).

## ECS Is the Foundation

- **Components** = pure data structs (`#[derive(Component)]` in `src/components/`)
- **Systems** = pure behavior unit structs implementing `specs::System` in `src/systems/`
- **Entities** = IDs created via `world.create_entity().with(...).build()`
- **Resources** = shared world state inserted via `world.insert(...)` (e.g. `City`, `GameState`)
- System execution order is fixed in `DispatcherBuilder` in `game.rs`

## Modularity & Encapsulation

- One concern per module. Keep modules small and focused.
- Never reach across module boundaries except through well-defined types (components, resources, traits).
- Prefer **composition over inheritance** — build behavior by combining components, not by nesting logic.
- Shared behavior = a `trait` (e.g. `UIElement`). Avoid duplicating logic across modules.

## Module Structure

```
src/
  components/   ← ECS data (one file per component)
  systems/      ← ECS behavior (one file per system)
  city/         ← Map and city generation
  deser/        ← XML/data loading (prefabs, items, templates)
  ui/           ← Rendering (elements/, modals/)
  input/        ← Keyboard/input handling
  service/      ← Layout/screen helpers
  util/         ← Shared utilities (rng, etc.)
```

- All modules are declared from `main.rs`. Add new modules there.
- Mirror directory structure with `mod` declarations.

## Parallelism

`specs` can run systems in parallel automatically — systems with non-overlapping `SystemData` are scheduled concurrently by the dispatcher. This project is currently **single-threaded** (no `rayon` dependency, no `parallel` feature on `specs`). The architecture already supports parallelism; it can be enabled later by adding rayon and using `par_join`.

To keep the door open:
- Declare only the storages a system truly needs in `SystemData`
- Systems that share a `WriteStorage` for the same component cannot run in parallel
- Prefer `ReadStorage` over `WriteStorage` wherever possible

## Game Loop

`Game::tick` (bracket-lib) → read input → optional sim tick (specs dispatcher) → UI render

Never put simulation logic in the UI layer. Never put rendering in systems.
